Whoa! Bill Gates looks so old now. I've literarily watched him and Microsoft grow from the early days of Windows 3.1. Watching him now trying to solve some of the World's tough problems, it's hard to imagine the then young Bill Gates some 30 years ago laser-focused trying to crush any company that would bring out any product to compete against Windows, Office and Internet Explorer. He was the personification of the evil villain trying to conquer the world. I'm still having difficulties separating the young and the old Bill Gates. At one point I even switched to using Corel OfficeSuite(Wordperfect) and Netscape Navigator and was even planning on moving to Linux desktop. Well, we all know how all those companies fared😄 They all faded while Microsoft thrived.
But, kudos to him for putting his money to help humanity.

snippet.textDisplay:
I appreciated this interview - a lot of the ideas and opinions shared were on the right track - but it's painfully obvious that Bill is pretty disconnected from the price of gasoline vs electricity, the 3x efficiency improvement in EV motors vs ICE, & the role Tesla has played and (being 5-8 years ahead in R&D) will continue to play in the future of the EV space. Pretty disappointed that the $180k Porsche was the first EV that was "good enough" for Bill Gates when the Model S has almost twice the range, better 0-60, and the biggest rapid charging network by a factor of 4X. I hope he enjoys his new super-polluting Yacht.
Edit: It's also obvious that the huge contributions the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation has poured into sponsorships of the educational YouTube community are to counter the bad press for his Yacht purchase. Seems disingenuous to me.

snippet.textDisplay:
My predictions for smartphones in 2 to 3 years.
- under display camera will be the solution to bezel, notch, pop up, punch hole camera.
- 144hz will be new standard for refresh rate
- solid state batteries will be able to store way more mAh but due to the devices being more powerful and demanding, battery life will be about the same, (batteries will last way longer than 2 to 3 years tho)
- smartphone sizes will stop increasing due to having all screen on the front and no bezels.
- flagship smartphones will have more Ram than most laptops
- the glass back trend will go back to metal back but which has wireless charging capabilities.
- charging slot will disappear and instead we will have an indent on the bottom to which a magnetic cable can charge the phone (without there being an actual “slot hole”)
